{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"3fb62105-4dea-4919-92d4-23a5f977f816","content":"The most likely cause: the .NET Android SDK's MSBuild targets have their **own JDK resolution logic** that may not pick up your shell `JAVA_HOME`, especially when building from an IDE (macOS GUI apps don't inherit shell environment variables).\n\n**Fix — explicitly tell MSBuild where your JDK is.** Add this to your `.csproj`:\n\n```xml\n<PropertyGroup Condition=\"$([MSBuild]::IsOSPlatform('osx'))\">\n  <JavaSdkDirectory>/Library/Java/JavaVirtualMachines/temurin-17.jdk/Contents/Home</JavaSdkDirectory>\n</PropertyGroup>\n```\n\nOr pass it on the command line:\n\n```bash\ndotnet build -p:JavaSdkDirectory=/Library/Java/JavaVirtualMachines/temurin-17.jdk/Contents/Home\n```\n\n**Verify your path first:**\n\n```bash\n/usr/libexec/java_home -v 17\n```\n\nUse whatever that returns as the value for `JavaSdkDirectory`.\n\nIf you'd rather use the JDK that ships with the MAUI workload (Microsoft Build of OpenJDK 17), you can reinstall it:\n\n```bash\ndotnet workload repair\n```\n\nThis ensures the bundled JDK is present and the build system will find it automatically without any extra configuration.\n\n---\n\nIf you share the **exact error message**, I can give a more targeted diagnosis.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"4f31e9f2-fb67-4729-84d4-8a4c5a37ba49","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is having a .NET MAUI Android build failure with a Java-related error on macOS. They have Adoptium Temurin JDK 17.0.12 installed with JAVA_HOME pointing to it.\n\nLet me think about what the common issue is here:\n\n.NET MAUI Android builds require a specific JDK version. Starting with .NET 8, MAUI/Android uses JDK 17. But there's a known issue with the JDK path on macOS specifically with Adoptium Temurin.\n\nOn macOS, Adoptium Temurin installs the JDK to a path like:\n\n\n`/Library/Java/JavaVirtualMachines/temurin-17.jdk/Contents/Home`\n\nThe .NET Android SDK has its own JDK detection logic that looks for JDK in specific locations, and there can be conflicts between what `JAVA_HOME` points to and what the .NET Android build system actually finds. The most common issue is a version mismatch—.NET 8 and 9 MAUI require JDK 17, while .NET 6 and 7 required JDK 11, so if they've upgraded their .NET version without updating their JDK, that would cause this failure.\n\nThere's also the Microsoft OpenJDK versus Adoptium Temurin distinction—the .NET Android SDK ships with and expects Microsoft's build of OpenJDK 17, so using a different JDK distribution like Temurin can create path conflicts or cause the build system to fall back to the bundled version. On macOS specifically, the Adoptium path needs to be set correctly for JAVA_HOME to point to the right location. Without seeing the actual error message, the most likely culprit is one of these configuration issues. **.NET MAUI / Android SDK bundles its own Microsoft OpenJDK 17** and the build system uses `$(JavaSdkDirectory)` which may not match `JAVA_HOME`. The MAUI build targets have their own JDK resolution logic.\n\nBut actually, the most common real-world issue people hit is:\n\n**JDK 17 is required but a different version is being picked up**, or **the Adoptium JDK isn't being recognized properly**.\n\nWait - actually, I think the most likely issue for a .NET MAUI Android build failure with Java on macOS with Temurin 17.0.12 is one of these:\n\n1. The .NET Android workload installs its own JDK (Microsoft OpenJDK) and that's what gets used, not the Temurin one. If the Microsoft one is a different version or corrupted, it fails.\n\n2. On macOS, `JAVA_HOME` should point to the correct path. For Adoptium Temurin, it's usually `/Library/Java/JavaVirtualMachines/temurin-17.jdk/Contents/Home`.\n\n3. There could be a version mismatch - some MAUI versions require specific JDK versions.\n\nActually, I think the most common and likely issue is simpler than all that. For .NET 8+ MAUI, the build uses JDK 17 and resolves `$(JavaSdkDirectory)` by checking `JAVA_HOME`, scanning `/Library/Java/JavaVirtualMachines/*/Contents/Home`, or falling back to the bundled Microsoft OpenJDK.\n\nThe user says `JAVA_HOME` points to Temurin 17.0.12 and `java -version` confirms it, so the issue is likely something else. Let me think about what Java-related errors commonly occur with MAUI Android builds - things like `UnsupportedClassVersionError` for wrong JDK versions, version parsing issues, or Android Gradle/d8/r8 compatibility problems with certain JDK versions.\n\nActually, I think the real issue might be that .NET MAUI on macOS doesn't respect the `JAVA_HOME` environment variable when launched from Visual Studio for Mac or certain IDE contexts, since GUI apps on macOS don't inherit shell environment variables. But the user could be building from the command line. The other possibility is that while Adoptium Temurin JDK 17.0.12+7 often works, .NET MAUI's Android build tools are specifically tested with and designed for the Microsoft Build of OpenJDK 17, and there can be subtle incompatibilities with other distributions. The most practical solution is that the .NET Android SDK actually installs its own JDK.\n\nThe best approach is to either use the Microsoft Build of OpenJDK 17 that comes with the .NET MAUI workload, or explicitly set the `JavaSdkDirectory` property in the project file to point to the correct JDK. On macOS specifically, even though `JAVA_HOME` is respected when using `dotnet build` from the terminal, the .NET Android SDK has its own JDK detection that can override it, so setting that MSBuild property is often the fix. There's also a chance that JDK 17.0.12 might be too new or have breaking changes that conflict with the specific MAUI version being used. to be more helpful here. The actual error message would clarify things, but the most common culprits are that MSBuild can't locate the JDK—either because `JAVA_HOME` isn't set in the build environment, or because the .NET Android workload expects JDK 17 specifically and isn't finding it. The quickest fix is usually setting `<JavaSdkDirectory>` in the project file to point directly to the JDK installation, or ensuring the Microsoft Build of OpenJDK 17 is installed with the workload. On macOS, the .NET MAUI/Android workload typically installs Microsoft's build of OpenJDK to a specific Xamarin directory, and the build system uses that by default rather than falling back to JAVA_HOME. If that installation is missing or corrupted, the build fails even though they have another JDK installed. Alternatively, if the build is using their Temurin JDK, there might be something specific about that distribution causing issues. The most practical fix is to explicitly configure MSBuild to use a specific JDK directory through a property setting.\n\nActually, stepping back—the core issue is likely that .NET MAUI Android specifically requires Microsoft's build of OpenJDK 17, not Adoptium Temurin. While both are OpenJDK 17, the .NET Android SDK validates against the Microsoft distribution specifically. The solution is either to install the Microsoft build through the workload command or manually point MSBuild to the correct JDK location. Setting the JavaSdkDirectory property in the .csproj file or via command line is the most reliable approach, since MSBuild often doesn't inherit JAVA_HOME from the shell environment on macOS. I'm realizing the user is asking a general question rather than about code in their workspace, so I should focus on giving a clear, practical answer about the root cause and solution.","outputTokens":3343,"requestId":"110B:1EB7C4:BCEA04:DD6F2F:69FE85DA"},"id":"794dd24a-ac48-446a-b048-e924047b2ff2","timestamp":"2026-05-09T00:55:58.639Z","parentId":"eabbcdc7-57be-43f8-accc-286c375389e0"}
